[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Assessing provider construction**\n\nI need to ensure that the provider has a public no-argument constructor and implements Runnable. The constructor or run method should invoke the Generator—I'm considering if ServiceLoader requires this during instantiation. I could call run to assert some condition. To trigger the Generator's static initialization, would it work to instantiate a new Generator with a path that doesn't exist? It seems that we don't need to invoke anything afterward since the constructor would already be in action.\n\n**Evaluating class structure and ServiceLoader**\n\nI'm considering whether it's okay to have an additional package-private class called `GeneratorTestServiceProvider` in the same file, even though it's not a test class. It might actually be fine. I need to ensure the ServiceLoader provider configuration is correct, including the file for the class name. Maybe creating a custom interface at the top-level could work better. Also, it's crucial that the service type class is visible to both parent and child loaders to avoid issues.\n\n**Considering ServiceLoader configuration**\n\nI'm thinking about whether the service type can be any class or interface, and it seems the provider must have a public no-argument constructor. The service configuration resource is named \"META-INF/services/java.lang.Runnable,\" and it might instantiate successfully. However, I wonder if the global resource could be included in native and ServiceLoader metadata, especially in native-image tests. For arbitrary service providers in a test app, a resource configuration might be necessary, and it could depend on whether the service provider feature is registered.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c6f8872be074a0a0169ef791d398c8193a0ddea9b3cd7bbbd\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp73lQenZgKjJFSHH5L_54c1VE8om1Cc6rwnsqMfssKt_mAO_ji